            </RevisionHistory>
            <Description>This data product contains the electron moments for the PEACE High Energy Electron Analyser (HEEA) 
                and/or Low Energy Electron Analyser (LEEA) sensors on the Cluster C2 spacecraft. 
                From 15th May 2011, the C2 LEEA instrument has an individual broken anode (anode 2 of 12), 
                while the C2 HEEA instrument was fully operational and the Data Processing Units (DPUs) 
                have been operating nominally in dual processor mode.
                The Plasma Electron And Current Experiment (PEACE) instrument is designed to measure
                the electron velocity distribution in the vicinity of its host spacecraft, covering
                an energy range of ~1 eV to ~26 keV and detecting electrons arriving from all possible
                directions. Each PEACE instrument has two sensor heads, LEEA and HEEA, which are
                mounted on opposite sides of the spacecraft such that the instantaneous field of view
                of one is the same as that seen by the other half a spacecraft rotation period later.
                LEEA and HEEA differ only in geometric factor (HEEA admits more electrons than LEEA
                when measuring the same energy range). Both sensors sample 4*pi steradians per spin.
                The full energy range is divided into 88 levels, however only a subset (60 or 30)
                of those can be sampled by each sensor in a given spin. Full coverage of the
                energy range may be achieved by using both HEEA and LEEA sensors together, each
                sampling a different (possibly overlapping) subset of the energy range.
                HEEA will normally cover the upper part of the energy range, since its larger
                geometric factor enables it to make better measurements of the more diffuse
                electron population expected at higher energies.
                LEEA is designed to specialise in the coverage of the lowest electron energies
                (including below 10 eV) but is also capable of covering the full energy range to
                26 keV.  The LEEA sensor has a smaller geometric factor appropriate for the
                higher fluxes of electrons usually found at lower energies, though LEEA does not
                always sample the lowest energies.</Description>
